  "texts": [
    "with leading term az k, k ∈ Q >1, which includes our case of interest), the Legendre transform is given as follows: If f (z) is such an exponent, its Legendre transform g(w) = f (w) is determined by the equations w = f ′ (z) and g(w) = f (z) -zw.",
    "The Legendre transform provides a permutation of the set of all circles of slope > 1 in I, and this is the way it is often presented in the literature.",
    "The crucial idea underlying the description of [Moc25] of the Fourier transform of Stokes data is that the Legendre transform can be seen in a stronger way, not only as a bijection between the sets of active circles of Θ and Θ, but for any active circle ⟨f ⟩ of Θ, as a homeomorphism between ⟨f ⟩ and the corresponding circle ⟨ f ⟩ of Θ.",
    "This can be observed as follows (what follows is similar to the presentation in [Dou23, §3.1], to which we refer for details): Let us denote the circle of directions at ∞ before Fourier transform by ∂ and the one after Fourier transform by ∂ ′.",
    "As explained in §2.1, a point of ⟨f ⟩ is a pair (θ, [ f ]) with θ ∈ ∂ and f a branch of f near θ (so f (z) is a holomorphic function on a small sector S(U) defined by a small neighbourhood U ⊂ ∂ of θ; we shrink U and S(U) if necessary)."
  ],
  "correct_citations": [
    "The crucial idea underlying the description of [Moc25] of the Fourier transform of Stokes data is that the Legendre transform can be seen in a stronger way, not only as a bijection between the sets of active circles of Θ and Θ, but for any active circle ⟨f ⟩ of Θ, as a homeomorphism between ⟨f ⟩ and the corresponding circle ⟨ f ⟩ of Θ."
